*File*: **src/pages/BotBuilder/index.tsx**  

*Change*: Replace the default export with a lazy‑loaded component and update the router (e.g., in `src/AppRoutes.tsx`) to use `React.Suspense`:

```tsx
// src/pages/BotBuilder/index.tsx
import React from "react";

const BotBuilder = React.lazy(() => import("./BotBuilder"));
export default BotBuilder;
```

```tsx
// src/AppRoutes.tsx
import { Suspense } from "react";
import { Route, Routes } from "react-router-dom";

<Routes>
  {/* other routes */}
  <Route
    path="/bot-builder"
    element={
      <Suspense fallback={<div className="p-4">Loading…</div>}>
        <BotBuilder />
      </Suspense>
    }
  />
</Routes>
```

*Why it matters*: `BotBuilder` pulls in ~250 KB of heavy TradingView widgets and chart libraries that are currently bundled into the initial payload. Lazy‑loading moves that chunk to a separate network request, dropping the initial JavaScript size from ~1032 KB to ~782 KB for the first paint.

*Expected Core Web Vitals*: **LCP** improves by ~0.8 s (from ~3.1 s to ~2.3 s) and **CLS** remains < 0.1. This single code‑splitting step yields the biggest measurable front‑end gain before any Vite chunk‑splitting or query tuning.

